 Project 
This is a HotelHub hotel management app built with:

Next.js 16 (App Router)
React 19
MongoDB Atlas + Mongoose
Material UI v9
NextAuth (login with email/password + Google)
Cloudinary (image uploads)
react-toastify (success/error popups)
framer-motion (table row animations)
The app has a public homepage, login/register, an admin dashboard, and a user dashboard. Most CRUD work follows the same pattern: Model → API Route → Table Component → Add/Edit/Delete Modals.

2. Folder Structure (Where Things Live)
myapp/
├── app/
│   ├── api/                    ← All backend API routes
│   │   ├── admin/              ← Admin-only APIs
│   │   │   ├── team/
│   │   │   ├── roomtype/
│   │   │   └── room/
│   │   ├── auth/[...nextauth]/ ← NextAuth login
│   │   └── team/               ← Public APIs
│   ├── model/                  ← Mongoose schemas
│   ├── component/              ← React components
│   │   └── dashboard/admin/    ← Admin CRUD pages
│   ├── dashboard/admin/        ← Admin page entry
│   └── layout.js
├── utils/
│   ├── dbConnect.js            ← MongoDB connection
│   └── authoptions.js          ← NextAuth config
├── middleware.js               ← Route protection
├── .env                        ← Environment variables
└── next.config.mjs
3. Import Paths — Read This Carefully
Your jsconfig.json maps @/* to the project root. Wrong imports are the #1 build error in this project.

File location	Correct import
utils/dbConnect.js
@/utils/dbConnect
utils/authoptions.js
@/utils/authoptions
app/model/team.js
@/app/model/team
app/model/room.js
@/app/model/room
app/model/facility.js
@/app/model/facility
Never write @/app/utils/dbConnect — that folder does not exist.

Never write @/model/team — models are inside app/model/.

4. Environment Variables (.env)
Your .env must use plain KEY=value format. No JavaScript, no module.exports.

DB_URI=mongodb+srv://USER:PASSWORD@cluster0.xxxxx.mongodb.net/hotelhubs?retryWrites=true&w=majority
NEXTAUTH_SECRET=your_random_secret_string
NEXTAUTH_URL=http://localhost:3000
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your_google_client_id
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=your_google_client_secret
NEXT_PUBLIC_CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME=your_cloud_name
CLOUDINARY_API_KEY=your_key
CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET=your_secret
API=http://localhost:3000/api
CLIENT_URL=http://localhost:3000
Rules:

No spaces around =
Client-side variables must start with NEXT_PUBLIC_
Restart npm run dev after changing .env
5. How to Create a New Feature (Step by Step)
When you want something new — say a “Services” module — follow this order:

Step 1: Create the Mongoose Model
File: app/model/service.js

import mongoose from "mongoose";
const serviceSchema = new mongoose.Schema(
  {
    name: { type: String, required: true },
    description: { type: String, default: null },
    image: { type: String, default: null },
  },
  { timestamps: true }
);
export default mongoose.models.Service ||
  mongoose.model("Service", serviceSchema);
Always use mongoose.models.X || mongoose.model(...) so Next.js hot reload does not crash.

Step 2: Create API Routes (CRUD)
List + Create: app/api/admin/service/route.js

import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import dbConnect from "@/utils/dbConnect";
import Service from "@/app/model/service";
export async function GET() {
  await dbConnect();
  try {
    const services = await Service.find({});
    return NextResponse.json(services);
  } catch (error) {
    return NextResponse.json({ err: error.message }, { status: 500 });
  }
}
export async function POST(req) {
  await dbConnect();
  const body = await req.json();
  const { name, description, image } = body;
  try {
    const service = await Service.create({ name, description, image });
    return NextResponse.json(service);
  } catch (error) {
    return NextResponse.json({ err: error.message }, { status: 500 });
  }
}
Update + Delete: app/api/admin/service/[id]/route.js

import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import dbConnect from "@/utils/dbConnect";
import Service from "@/app/model/service";
export async function PUT(req, context) {
  await dbConnect();
  const { id } = await context.params;
  try {
    const body = await req.json();
    const updated = await Service.findByIdAndUpdate(id, body, { new: true });
    if (!updated) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "Not found" }, { status: 404 });
    }
    return NextResponse.json(updated);
  } catch (error) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: error.message }, { status: 500 });
  }
}
export async function DELETE(req, context) {
  await dbConnect();
  const { id } = await context.params;
  try {
    const deleted = await Service.findByIdAndDelete(id);
    if (!deleted) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "Not found" }, { status: 404 });
    }
    return NextResponse.json(deleted);
  } catch (error) {
    return NextResponse.json({ err: error.message }, { status: 500 });
  }
}
Note: In Next.js 16, always use await context.params to get the id.

Step 3: Create Admin UI (Copy Team Module Style)
Create a folder: app/component/dashboard/admin/service/

You need these files (copy from team/ folder):

File	Purpose
ServiceTable.js
Main table + fetch data
AddServiceModal.js
Create form
EditServiceModal.js
Edit form
DeleteServiceModal.js
Confirm delete
style.js
Shared styles
Step 4: Register in Admin Dashboard
In app/component/dashboard/admin/Admin.js:

Import your component at the top
Add a navigation item in the sidebar
Add a case in the page router:
case "/service":
  return (
    <Box sx={{ backgroundColor: "#000" }}>
      <ServiceTable />
    </Box>
  );
6. Admin Table Pattern (The Heart of CRUD UI)
Every admin table in this project follows the same structure. Team module is the gold standard — copy it first.

State you always need:
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
const [page, setPage] = useState(0);
const [rowsPerPage, setRowsPerPage] = useState(5);
const [openAddModal, setOpenAddModal] = useState(false);
const [openEditModal, setOpenEditModal] = useState(false);
const [openDeleteModal, setOpenDeleteModal] = useState(false);
const [currentItem, setCurrentItem] = useState(null);
Fetch on mount:
useEffect(() => {
  fetchItems();
}, []);
const fetchItems = async () => {
  try {
    setLoading(true);
    const response = await fetch(`/api/admin/service`);
    const data = await response.json();
    setItems(data);
  } catch (error) {
    toast.error("Failed to fetch data");
  } finally {
    setLoading(false);
  }
};
After Add / Edit / Delete — update UI:
// Add
const handleAddSuccess = (newItem) => {
  setItems((prev) => [...prev, newItem]);
  setOpenAddModal(false);
};
// Edit
const handleEditSuccess = (updatedItem) => {
  setItems((prev) =>
    prev.map((item) => (item._id === updatedItem._id ? updatedItem : item))
  );
  setOpenEditModal(false);
};
// Delete
const handleDeleteSuccess = (deletedId) => {
  setItems((prev) => prev.filter((item) => item._id !== deletedId));
  setOpenDeleteModal(false);
};
Delete click — pass the correct object:
const handleDeleteClick = (item) => {
  setCurrentItem(item);   // Pass the actual record, not a related record
  setOpenDeleteModal(true);
};
7. Modal Pattern
Add Modal API call:
const response = await fetch(`/api/admin/service`, {
  method: "POST",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
  body: JSON.stringify({ name, description, image }),
});
const data = await response.json();
if (!response.ok) throw new Error(data.err || "Failed");
onSuccess(data);
toast.success("Added successfully");
Edit Modal API call:
const response = await fetch(`/api/admin/service/${item._id}`, {
  method: "PUT",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
  body: JSON.stringify(formData),
});
Delete Modal — always check response:
const response = await fetch(`/api/admin/service/${member._id}`, {
  method: "DELETE",
});
const data = await response.json();
if (!response.ok) {
  throw new Error(data.error || "Delete failed");
}
onSuccess(member._id);
toast.success("Deleted successfully");
Never show success without checking response.ok.

8. Image Upload (Cloudinary Pattern)
Used in Team, Room Categories, Profile, etc.

// 1. User picks file → preview with FileReader
const reader = new FileReader();
reader.onloadend = () => {
  setForm((prev) => ({
    ...prev,
    image: file,
    previewImage: reader.result,
  }));
};
reader.readAsDataURL(file);
// 2. On submit → upload to Cloudinary first
const imageData = new FormData();
imageData.append("file", form.image);
imageData.append("upload_preset", "ml_default");
const response = await fetch(
  `https://api.cloudinary.com/v1_1/${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME}/image/upload`,
  { method: "POST", body: imageData }
);
const data = await response.json();
const imageUrl = data.secure_url;
// 3. Save URL (not the file) to your API
body: JSON.stringify({ name, image: imageUrl })
9. MUI v9 Styling Rules (Very Important)
This project uses MUI v9. Old MUI v5 props will cause console errors.

Old (don't use)	New (use this)
<Grid item xs={12} sm={6}>
<Grid size={{ xs: 12, sm: 6 }}>
InputLabelProps={{ style: { color: "#8A12FC" } }}
slotProps={{ inputLabel: { sx: { color: "#8A12FC" } } }}
InputProps={{ startAdornment: ... }}
slotProps={{ input: { startAdornment: ... } }}
Standard TextField style in this project:
slotProps={{
  inputLabel: { sx: { color: "#8A12FC" } },
}}
sx={{
  input: { color: "black" },
  "& .MuiOutlinedInput-root": {
    "& fieldset": { borderColor: "#8A12FC" },
    "&:hover fieldset": { borderColor: "#8A12FC" },
    "&.Mui-focused fieldset": { borderColor: "#8A12FC" },
  },
}}
Or put shared styles in style.js as textFieldStyles and spread them.

Brand colors used across admin:
Primary purple: #8A12FC
Hover purple: #7a0eeb
Edit icon: #3f51b5
Delete icon: #ff5252
10. Shared Style File Pattern (style.js)
Every admin module has a style.js with:

export const colors = { edit: "#3f51b5", delete: "#ff5252", ... };
export const modalStyle = { position: "absolute", top: "50%", ... };
export const StyledPaper = styled(Paper)({ ... });
export const StyledTableHeader = styled(TableHead)({ ... });
export const StyledHeaderCell = styled(TableCell)({ ... });
export const AnimatedTableRow = motion(TableRow);
export const textFieldStyles = { slotProps: { ... }, sx: { ... } };
Copy from team/style.js or manageroomcategories/styles.js.

11. Authentication (NextAuth)
Config: utils/authoptions.js
API route: app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.js
Login page: app/login/page.js
Session in layout: <SessionProvider> in app/layout.js
Protected routes: middleware.js
Admin APIs under /api/admin/* are protected by middleware. User must be logged in.

Test auth: Open http://localhost:3000/api/auth/session — should return JSON, not HTML.

12. Room Categories — Special Case (Two Collections)
Room management uses two linked collections:

Collection	Stores
roomtypes
Category name only
rooms
Price, image, capacity, linked via roomtype_id
When adding a room category, the API creates both:

const roomtype = await RoomType.create({ name });
const room = await Room.create({ roomtype_id: roomtype._id });
When deleting a room category, delete related rooms, facilities, images, and room numbers too.

Display rule: Show roomtype.name in the table, not room.roomtype_id.name.

Delete rule: Pass roomtype._id to delete API, not room._id.

13. Common Mistakes and How to Avoid Them
Mistake	Fix
Export default doesn't exist
Add export default function ComponentName() wrapper
Can't resolve '@/app/utils/dbConnect'
Use @/utils/dbConnect
Can't resolve '@/model/team'
Use @/app/model/team
Delete shows success but nothing removed
Check response.ok; pass correct _id
Table shows "N/A"
Display the right field from the right object
InputLabelProps / InputProps / item warnings
Use MUI v9 slotProps and size
NextAuth CLIENT_FETCH_ERROR
Fix turbopack root in next.config.mjs
MongoDB timeout 98 seconds
Fix .env format; whitelist IP in Atlas
.env not loading
No module.exports; use KEY=value only
14. next.config.mjs (Required)
const nextConfig = {
  turbopack: {
    root: import.meta.dirname,
  },
};
export default nextConfig;
Without this, Next.js may use the wrong project root and all API routes return 404.

15. Master AI Prompt (Paste This When Building New Features)
Copy the block below when asking an AI to build something in this project:

PROJECT CONTEXT PROMPT

You are working on HotelHub, a Next.js 16 App Router hotel admin project.
STACK: React 19, MUI v9, Mongoose, MongoDB Atlas, NextAuth, Cloudinary, react-toastify, framer-motion.
IMPORT RULES:
- dbConnect: @/utils/dbConnect
- Models: @/app/model/[name]
- Never use @/app/utils/ or @/model/
API PATTERN:
- Create app/api/admin/[feature]/route.js for GET + POST
- Create app/api/admin/[feature]/[id]/route.js for PUT + DELETE
- Always await dbConnect() first
- Use await context.params for dynamic id in Next.js 16
- Return NextResponse.json()
- Check response.ok on frontend before showing success
UI PATTERN (copy from team module):
- ServiceTable.js with fetch, pagination, modals
- AddModal, EditModal, DeleteModal
- style.js with StyledPaper, colors, modalStyle, textFieldStyles
- Purple theme #8A12FC for buttons and inputs
- toast.success / toast.error for feedback
MUI V9 RULES:
- Grid: use size={{ xs: 12, sm: 6 }} not item xs sm
- TextField: use slotProps not InputLabelProps or InputProps
IMAGE UPLOAD:
- Upload to Cloudinary with NEXT_PUBLIC_CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME
- Store secure_url in database, not file object
DELETE:
- Pass correct document _id to DELETE API
- Always check response.ok before success toast
- Update state with filter/map or refetch
ADMIN INTEGRATION:
- Register component in Admin.js navigation and case switch
Do not over-engineer. Match existing team/room module code style exactly.
